<p style="text-align:justify;">and Relieving the eye from the barren Ruggedness of the Hill, which is certainly one of the bleakest spots in his Majest<span class="DelHand-author">ee</span><span class="AddHand-author">y</span>'s dominions, 'tho at present the Seat of Justice, honour, politeness, and the most liberal hospitality<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">Although the position of S<sup>t</sup> Joseph's is far from being the most judicious that might have been chosen for a permanent Post, yet as a great deal of money has been already laid upon it all that is now left to the wisdom of government is to improve to the best advantage what can be no longer conveniently changed.  If I might be permitted to offer an opinion, where so many of superior knowledge and more extensive views are to be had, I Should think the first step to be taken would be to have <span class="AddHand-author">the</span> Island Surveyed and laid out into one and two hundred Acre lots with encouragement to Settlers proportioned to the trouble and expense of coming Such a distance, which however, might be much alleviated by the Kings Vessel which often comes to the Fort not half loaded<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  A Road Should be opened the length of the Island which would terminate at the north east channel &amp; which would enable the Garrison to obstruct the invasion of S<sup>t</sup> Mar<span class="DelHand-author">ie</span><span class="AddHand-author">y</span>'s from that quarter, <span class="DelHand-author">and</span> a Second Should be</p>

